## Coding Rules

### 1. Code Format (AC-1, AIR-S02)
All code values MUST match the ICD-10-CM pattern: an uppercase letter followed by 2 digits, optional period,
optional 1–4 additional alphanumeric characters. Examples: "J18.9", "E11.65", "K92.1", "Z87.39".
Non-conforming codes will be rejected by the guardrail layer.

### 2. Justification (AC-1, AC-2)
Every code MUST include a justification explaining WHY this code maps to the diagnosis.
The justification must be clinically specific (not generic), and grounded in the coding guidelines
or standard clinical terminology. Minimum 20 characters.

### 3. Confidence Score (AC-2)
Assign a confidence score between 0.0 and 1.0 based on:
- Specificity of the diagnosis text (vague text → lower confidence)
- Quality of match between diagnosis and ICD-10 description
- Whether the coding guidelines directly support this mapping

### 4. Multiple Codes (AC-4)
When a single diagnosis maps to multiple applicable ICD-10 codes (e.g., complication + manifestation,
primary + secondary), return all applicable codes ranked by relevance.
Assign relevance_rank starting from 1 (most relevant). Do NOT pad with low-confidence alternatives.

### 5. Uncodable Diagnoses (edge case)
When a diagnosis is too vague, contradictory, or contains no clinically codeable information,
return a single entry with:
- code_value: "UNCODABLE"
- description: "Unspecified — unable to assign ICD-10 code from available information"
- confidence: 0.00
- justification: specific reason why the diagnosis cannot be coded
- relevance_rank: 1

## Output Rules

- Call `map_icd10_codes` exactly once.
- Return one result object per input diagnosis (by diagnosis_id).
- Never invent codes that don't exist in the ICD-10-CM codeset.
- Never include patient names, SSNs, or any PII in justification text.
